{
  "answer": "**In the *Vrhaspatitattva*, a Kawi Śaiva philosophical text attributed to Bṛhaspati, *cetana* (Conscious Principle) and *acetana* (Unconscious Principle) are presented as the two supreme *tattvas* (principles of reality), from which all other *tattvas* arise.**[^1][^2]\n\n*Cetana* is defined as that which possesses the nature of *jñāna* (knowledge): it knows, is never subject to forgetting (*lupa*), remains eternally aware (*jñānamaya*) at all times, and is unobscured (*nirākula*).[^2] It has three distinct forms: *Paramaśivatattva* (the highest, immeasurable, all-pervading, and sovereign), *Sadāśivatattva* (active, omniscient, omnipotent, seated on a lotus throne of four *śaktis*—powers), and *Śivatattva* (pure consciousness, stained by *mala*—impurity—when pervading lower *tattvas* like *māyā*, becoming the dazed *ātmā* or soul).[^2][^3]\n\n*Acetana*, by contrast, is devoid of knowledge (*ajñāna*), likened to a stone (*aśma*), void, and inert.[^2] It exemplifies unconsciousness, such as *māyātattva* (delusive principle, empty and transparent) and *pradhānatattva* (its gross child, causing forgetfulness in the soul).[^3][^4]\n\nTheir conjunction (*cetana*-*acetana*-saṃyoga*) generates the full *sarvatattva* (all principles): *pradhāna*, *triguṇa* (*sattva*, *rajas*, *tamas*), *buddhi*, *ahaṅkāra*, senses (*indriya*), and *pañcamahābhūta* (gross elements).[^2] This framework explains *saṃsāra* (cycle of rebirth), where *cetana* (as soul) is veiled by *acetana* principles, leading to bondage until liberated via knowledge (*jñāna*), dispassion (*vairāgya*), and yoga.[^3][^5]\n\n[^1]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-04d69c).\n[^2]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-c31df3).\n[^3]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-643885).\n[^4]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1, [passage](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-695576).\n[^5]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-724e96).",
